    <text>
        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Johns Hopkins University&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Baltimore&#44; Nov. 17 1889<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Dr Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>I have been investi&#45;<lb/>gating the history of the Shofar and<lb/> I should very much like to have<lb/> information from you &#40;if you can spare<lb/> the time&#41; upon certain points.<lb/></p>
            <p>Where are shofars made now&#63;  Can<lb/> you put me in communication with<lb/> some of the people who make them<lb/> so that I could get an accurate<lb/> description of the process.<lb/></p>
            <p>Mishna Rosh ha Shanah says<lb/> that any horn can be used<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>except that of a cow.  Do you<lb/> remember any passage which speaks<lb/> of the employment of any other than<lb/> a ram&#39;s&#45;horn&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>Is there any intimation that the<lb/> horn of a wild goat or chamois<lb/> was used&#63;  Any notion of a<lb/> connection between the shofar &#38;<lb/> the sacrifice of the goat on Yom Kippur&#63;<lb/>  Is there any midrash connecting<lb/> the shofar &#38; the sacrifice of Isaac&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>Who composed &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#38;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>I should like very much to have<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>a photograph of your old Italian shofar<lb/> together with its measurement and<lb/> its history as far as you know it.<lb/>  I hope that you are not overwhelmed<lb/> by all these questions.<lb/></p>
            <p>Sincerely Yours<lb/>
                Cyrus Adler<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
